04269nam a22005895i 9789633865767DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20222022hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338657677 a10.1515/97896338657672doi  a(DE-B1597)633573  a(OCoLC)1323328215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aHV8224 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a363.2094709/034qDLC223/eng/202206031 aAbbott, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistorical Studies in Eastern Europe and Eurasia. Policemen of the Tsar :bLocal Police in an Age of Upheaval /cRobert J. Abbott. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (235 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies in Eastern Europe and Eurasia00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface -- tGlossary of Russian Police Terms -- tChapter 1 The Local Police at Mid-Century -- tChapter 2 The Rural Police -- tChapter 3 Metropolitan and Municipal Police -- tChapter 4 From Stalemate to Forced Resolution -- tChapter 5 A Police Balance Sheet -- tChapter 6 Consequences and Implications -- tAppendix. Police in the Borderlands -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aFounded by Peter the Great in 1718, Russia's police were key instruments of tsarist power. In the reign of Alexander II (1855-1881), local police forces took on new importance. The liberation of 23 million serfs from landlord control, growing fear of crime, and the terrorist violence of the closing years challenged law enforcement with new tasks that made worse what was already a staggering burden. ("I am obliged to inform Your Imperial Highness that the police often fail to carry out their assignments and, when they do execute them, they do so poorly because of their moral corruption...") This book describes the regime's decades-long struggle to reform and strengthen the police. The author reviews the local police's role and performance in the mid-nineteenth century and the implications of the largely unsuccessful effort to transform them. From a longer-term perspective, the study considers how the police's systemic weaknesses undermined tsarist rule, impeded a range of liberalizing reforms, perpetuated reliance on the military to maintain law and order, and gave rise to vigilante justice. While its primary focus is on European Russia, the analysis also covers much of the imperial periphery, discussing the police systems in the Baltic Provinces, Congress Poland, the Caucasus, Central Asia, and Siberia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPolicezRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aEmancipation.  aGreat Reforms.  acourts.  arevolution.  azemstvos.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633865767?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865767zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865767/original  a978-3-11-078048-2 Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA